Dates and Times

Using the lubridate package

Material adapted from the textbook, “R for Data Science” (R4DS) by Hadley Wickham and Garret Grolemund. The official website of the textbook is http://r4ds.had.co.nz/

Load the required packages

library(tidyverse)

Introduction

  • Does every year have 365 days?

  • Does every day have 24 hours?

  • Does every minute have 60 seconds?

Do you know the full rule for determining if a year is a leap year? (It has three parts.) You might have remembered that many parts of the world use daylight savings time (DST), so that some days have 23 hours, and others have 25. You might not have known that some minutes have 61 seconds because every now and then leap seconds are added because the Earth’s rotation is gradually slowing down.

We will focus on the lubridate package, which makes it easier to work with dates and times in R. lubridate is not part of core tidyverse because you only need it when you’re working with dates/times. We will also need nycflights13 for practice data.

library(lubridate)
library(nycflights13)

Creating date/times

There are three types of date/time data that refer to an instant in time:

  • A date. Tibbles print this as <date>.

  • A time within a day. Tibbles print this as <time>.

  • A date-time is a date plus a time: it uniquely identifies an instant in time (typically to the nearest second). Tibbles print this as <dttm>. Elsewhere in R these are called POSIXct.

To get the current date or date-time you can use today() or now():

# use today and now 
today()
[1] "2020-01-29"
now()
[1] "2020-01-29 21:18:50 EST"

From strings

Date/time data often comes as strings. Using the helpers provided by lubridate, we can automatically work out the format once we specify the order of the component.

To use them, identify the order in which year, month, and day appear in your dates, then arrange “y”, “m”, and “d” in the same order. That gives you the name of the lubridate function that will parse your date. For example

ymd("20171231")
[1] "2017-12-31"
ymd("1996(&(*&1221")
[1] "1996-12-21"

mdy("OCT&(*&(&*12((*&(21")
[1] "2021-10-12"
#this uses regular expression to match the format

ymd_hms("1017/12/21 10:10:00")
[1] "1017-12-21 10:10:00 UTC"

Notice that you can also use these functions with unquoted numbers

ymd() and friends create dates. To create a date-time, add an underscore and one or more of “h”, “m”, and “s” to the name of the parsing function:

Coordinated Universal Time abbreviated to UTC, is the primary time standard by which the world regulates clocks and time. It is within about 1 second of mean solar time at 0 longitude,and it does not observe daylight saving time.

You can also force the creation of a date-time from a date by supplying a timezone:


now()
[1] "2020-01-29 21:18:50 EST"
ymd_hms(now(), tz = "EST")
[1] "2020-01-29 21:18:50 EST"

From individual components

Instead of a single string, sometimes you will have the individual components of the date-time spread across multiple columns. This is what we have in the flights data:

flights %>% 
  select(year, month, day, hour, minute)

To create a date/time from this sort of input, use make_date() for dates, or make_datetime() for date-times:

flights %>% 
  select(year, month, hour, minute) %>% 
  mutate(departure=make_datetime(year, month, hour, minute))
NA
NA

We can do the same thing for each of the four time columns in flights. The times are represented in a slightly odd format, so we use modulus arithmetic to pull out the hour and minute components.

A familiar use of modular arithmetic is in the 12-hour clock, in which the day is divided into two 12-hour periods. If the time is 7:00 now, then 8 hours later it will be 3:00. Usual addition would suggest that the later time should be 7 + 8 = 15, but this is not the answer because clock time “wraps around” every 12 hours. This computation can be done following “arithmetic modulo 12”: the operator in R to do this is %% to find the value of \(15 \mod 12\), that is, the remainder of dividing 15 by 12

15%%12
[1] 3

In the flights data set, the variables dep_time, arr_time, sched_dep_time, and sched_arr_time are actually given in military time, i.e. a 24-hour clock where 1300 refers to 1 pm, and 2359 refers to 11:59 pm

%% indicates \((x \mod y)\) and %/% indicates integer division. It is guaranteed that x == (x %% y) + y * ( x %/% y ) (up to rounding error)

First, let us create a function called make_datetime_100

2359 %/% 100
[1] 23
500 %/% 100
[1] 5
500 %% 100
[1] 0
make_datetime_100 <- function(year, month, day, time){
  make_datetime(year, month, day, time %/% 100, time%%100)
}

Now we use this function to create a new data frame with date-time values in the four different variables we are interested in

flights_dt <- flights %>% 
  filter(!is.na(dep_time), !is.na(arr_time)) %>% 
  mutate(
    dep_time = make_datetime_100(year, month, day, dep_time), 
    arr_time = make_datetime_100(year, month, day, arr_time), 
    sched_dep_time = make_datetime_100(year, month, day, sched_dep_time),
    sched_arr_time = make_datetime_100(year, month, day, sched_arr_time),
    
    
  ) %>% 
  select(origin, dest, ends_with("delay"), ends_with("time")) #all the columns ends with delay and time

Double check our new data frame

flights_dt

With this data, we can visualize the distribution of departure times within a day:

#damn this gg plot is pretty neat
flights_dt %>%
  filter(dep_time < ymd(20130102)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(dep_time)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 600) # 600 s = 10 minutes

or with a histogram

flights_dt %>%
  filter(dep_time < ymd(20130102)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(dep_time)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 600) # 600 s = 10 minutes

Note that when you use date-times in a numeric context (like in a histogram), 1 means 1 second, so a binwidth of 86400 means one day. For dates, 1 means 1 day.

From other types

You may want to switch between a date-time and a date. That’s the job of as_datetime() and as_date():

Date-time components

You can pull out individual parts of the date with the accessor functions year(), month(), mday() (day of the month), yday() (day of the year), wday() (day of the week), hour(), minute(), and second().

# day of the month
mday(today())
[1] 29
# day of the week
wday(today())
[1] 4
# day of the year
yday(today())
[1] 29

In yday(), 1 means Sunday, 7 means Saturday.

Consider for instance July 7th 1969 at 8:18 pm

mydatetime <- ymd_hms("1969-07-20 08:18:04pm", tz = "UTC")

we can access the different components of this date-time as follows:

year(mydatetime)
[1] 1969
month(mydatetime, label=T)
[1] Jul
12 Levels: Jan < Feb < Mar < Apr < May < Jun < Jul < Aug < ... < Dec
mday(mydatetime)
[1] 20
wday(mydatetime, label=T)
[1] Sun
Levels: Sun < Mon < Tue < Wed < Thu < Fri < Sat

We can use wday() to see that more flights depart during the week than on the weekend:

flights_dt %>% mutate(wday =wday(dep_time, label=T)) %>% 
  #group_by(wday) %>% 
  #count() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=wday)) + geom_bar()

There is an interesting pattern if we look at the average departure delay by minute within the hour.

It looks like flights leaving in minutes 20-30 and 50-60 have much lower delays than the rest of the hour!

Time Spans

We discuss three important classes that represent time spans:

  • durations, which represent an exact number of seconds.

  • periods, which represent human units like weeks and months.

  • intervals, which represent a starting and ending point.

Durations

In R, when you subtract two dates, you get a difftime object:

# How old is your friend?
rei_age <- today() - ymd(20120214)
rei_age
Time difference of 2906 days
class(rei_age) 
[1] "difftime"

duration <- as.duration(rei_age)

Durations come with a bunch of convenient constructors:

dyears(1) + dweeks(12)
[1] "38793600s (~1.23 years)"

You can add and multiply durations:

Some arithmetic:

one_pm <- ymd_hms("2016-03-12 13:00:00", tz = "America/New_York")

one_pm
[1] "2016-03-12 13:00:00 EST"
#> [1] "2016-03-12 13:00:00 EST"
one_pm + ddays(1) #same as datetime time delta in python account for daylight saving EDT represents daylight saving time
[1] "2016-03-13 14:00:00 EDT"

Why is one day after 1pm on March 12, 2pm on March 13?!

If you look carefully at the date you might also notice that the time zones have changed. Because of DST, March 12 only has 23 hours, so if you add a full days worth of seconds we end up with a different time.

To solve this problem, lubridate provides periods.

Periods

These are time spans but do not have a fixed length in seconds, instead they work with “human” times, like days and months. That allows them work in a more intuitive way:

Sys.timezone(
)
[1] "America/New_York"

Compared to durations, periods are more likely to do what you expect:

# A leap year

# Daylight Savings Time

Let us use periods to fix an oddity related to our flight dates: Some planes appear to have arrived at their destination before they departed from New York City.

These are overnight flights. We used the same date information for both the departure and the arrival times, but these flights arrived on the following day. We can fix this by adding days(1) to the arrival time of each overnight flight.

flights_dt <- 
  
  
Error: Incomplete expression: flights_dt <-

overnight is equal to TRUE (1) or FALSE (0). So if it is an overnight flight, this becomes 1 day, and if not, then overnight = 0, and no days are added to the date.

Now all of our flights obey the laws of physics.

Time zones

R uses the international standard IANA time zones

These use a consistent naming scheme “/”, typically in the form “/”. Examples include “America/New_York”, “Europe/Paris”, and “Pacific/Auckland”.

You can find out what R thinks your current time zone is with Sys.timezone():

Unless other specified, lubridate always uses UTC. UTC (Coordinated Universal Time) is the standard time zone used by the scientific community and roughly equivalent to its predecessor GMT (Greenwich Mean Time). It does not have DST, which makes a convenient representation for computation.
